surveys.narrative: A TOTAL OF 30 RAINBOW TROUT WERE SAMPLED BY 2 GILLNETS. TWO SIZE GROUPS WERE REPRESENTED - 7 TO 9 INCHES AND 11 TO 13 INCHES. THE LARGER GROUP WAS FAR LESS NUMEROUS POSSIBLY INDICATING HIGH MORTALITY (FISHING OR NATURAL) SINCE EQUAL NUMBERS ARE STOCKED EACH YEAR.

Willard Lake is one of four designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker area. It is located two and ? miles north and one and ? miles east of Backus. Other stream trout lakes are Perch (located in the Foothills State Forest), Teepee (located three miles south and one mile west of Whipholt), and Hazel (located four miles west of Longville) Lakes. Willard Lake has been a designated trout since 1956. The only type of trout that has been stocked has rainbow trout.The population assessment was conducted because of angler complaints of poor fishing. A total of five rainbow trout were sampled. These trout ranged in length from 7.3 to 10.2 inches and had an average length and weight of 9.2 inches and 0.3 pounds. All five trout were one year old fish.

Willard Lake (11-564; Lake Class 21) has a total surface area of 7.4 acres and a shoreline length of 0.4 miles. A county owned carry-in public access is located on the north shore of the lake. Willard Lake is one of five lakes in the Walker Fisheries Management Area designated as a stream trout lake and stocked annually with rainbow trout. The trout population in Willard Lake depends upon stocking because rainbow trout do not naturally reproduce in this lake. The rainbow trout catch rate increased in 2003 when compared to the 2002 survey. The 2003 catch rate (20.0 per lift) met the long-range goal of 10 to 20 fish per lift. Two year-classes of rainbow trout were captured with a mean length of 11 inches and the lengths ranged from 8 to 14 inches. Since 1998, Fisheries personnel have been sampling zooplankton, the tiny animals on which Willard Lake rainbow trout feed. The quantity of zooplankton available in Willard Lake is relatively low and biologists are currently investigating the annual fluctuation in trout survival by examining the food supply.

Willard Lake (11-0564-00 Lake Class 21) has a total surface area of 7.4 acres and a shoreline length of 0.43 miles. A county owned carry-in public access is located on the north shore of the lake. Willard Lake is one of five lakes in the Walker Fisheries Management Area designated as a stream trout lake and stocked annually with rainbow trout. The trout population in Willard Lake depends upon stocking because rainbow trout do not naturally reproduce in this lake. Prior to 2006, DNR staff had stocked Willard Lake with fingerling trout in the fall, but beginning in 2006, a switch was made to spring stocking with yearlings in an effort to improve trout survival.

Six rainbow trout were captured in the 2006 DNR sampling. The mean length of these trout was 12.8 inches, and they ranged from 11.7 to 13.5 inches.

Black crappie ranging from 5 to 9 inches were caught in DNR nets. Yellow perch from 5 to 9 inches were also caught. The presence of black crappie and yellow perch was the result of illegal stocking, which may well have a negative impact on the rainbow trout population.

Since 1998, Fisheries personnel have been sampling zooplankton, the tiny animals on which Willard Lake rainbow trout feed. The quantity of zooplankton available in Willard Lake is relatively low and biologists are currently investigating the annual fluctuation in trout survival by examining the food supply.

The population assessment was initiated because of complaints from anglers of not catching trout on Willard Lake. In 1994, there was similar complaints on most area stream trout lakes. Willard Lake is one of five designatedstream trout lakes in the Walker area and has had this distinction since 1956. All trout existing in the lakeare the result of stocking. The only species of trout stocked in Willard Lake has been rainbow trout.During the 1994 assessment a total of 10 rainbow trout were sampled for a catch-per-unit-of-effort of 5.0/gillnetlift. This catch was considerably lower than catches recorded in 1992 (14.5/lift) and 1988 (15.0/lift). The 1994sample ranged in length from 5.7 - 9.8 inches and had a mean length of 8.1 inches. All the rainbow trout areprobably one year old fish with anglers harvesting most trout before they can reach age 2.No other species of fish was sampled in the gill nets. DNR personnel will again be sampling Willard Lake in 1995.

Willard Lake (11-564; Lake Class 21) has a total surface area of 7.4 acres and a shoreline length of 0.4 miles. There is a County owned dirt path public access on the north shore of the lake. Willard Lake is one of five lakes in the Walker Fisheries Management Area designated as a stream trout lake and stocked annually. No rainbow trout were collected during the 2001 gill net survey. This observation is consistent with previous assessments when no or very few rainbow trout were collected. Preliminary findings investigating the apparent poor survival of rainbow trout in Willard Lake suggests a poor food supply. Consequently, biologists at the Walker Fisheries office are currently examining the quantity and quality of available forage for rainbow trout in Willard Lake.

Willard Lake is one of five designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker area. Other stream-trout lakes in the Walker area are Diamond, Hazel, Perch, and Teepee. Willard Lake was first used as a stream-trout lake in 1956. Anglers have reported poor fishing success the last few years. Rainbow trout have been stocked into Willard Lake since 1955. Three rainbow trout were sampled in 2000, and all the fish came from the 1999 stocking. The average length of rainbow trout was 8.8 inches. Low density and biomass of zooplankton which is an important food for rainbow trout may be a contributing factor to the low number of fish sampled in Willard Lake.

Willard Lake is one of five designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker area. It has had this designation since 1956. It is located two miles north and two miles east of Backus and south of Ox Yoke Lake. Other trout lakes in the Walker fisheries area are Hazel (located 3.5 miles west of Longville), Teepee (located three miles south and one mile west of Whipholt), Perch (located five miles west of Backus), and Diamond (located five miles north and three miles east of Hackensack). All trout existing in the lake are the result of stocking. Various strains of rainbow trout have been stocked over the years. For the past several years, anglers have reported poor angling success in Willard Lake.Testnetting resulted in 13 trout being sampled. This was slightly more than what was found in 1995 (5) but considerably less than in 1989 and 1992 surveys. At various times through the summer, the lake was sampled for zooplankton (tiny animals that are important food for trout). Low numbers of zooplankton were found. Due to what appears to be limited food availability, the stocking quota was reduced by 50 percent. Further assessments will determine if this reduction has the potential to improve angling success.

Willard Lake is one of five designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker area. It has had this designation since 1956. Other trout lakes in the Walker Fisheries Area are Hazel (located 3.5 miles west of Longville), Teepee (located three miles south and one mile west of Whipholt), Perch (located 5 miles west of Backus), and Diamond (located five miles north and three miles east of Hackensack). All trout existing in the lake are the result of stocking. Various strains of rainbow trout have been stocked over the years. For the past several years, anglers have reported poor angling success in Willard Lake.Testnetting in 1999 resulted in no rainbow trout being sampled. In 1998 and 1999, at various times throughout the summer, the lake was sampled for zooplankton (tiny animals that are important food for trout). Low numbers of zooplankton were found in Willard Lake. Due to what appears to be limited food availability, the stocking quota was reduced by 50 percent starting in 1998. The 1999 zooplankton samples continued to show low numbers of zooplankton. Further assessments will determine if this reduction in stocking has the potential to increase zooplankton numbers, thus improving trout survival and angling.
